display="inline"><![CDATA[\ker (\pi )\cong  N]]></fr:tex>. We want to find a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi \colon  M/N\to  M]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi \circ \psi =\mathop {\textrm {id}}\nolimits _{M/N}]]></fr:tex>. Then the image of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi (M/N)=T]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>(1) Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M/N]]></fr:tex> is free, we can always find such a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\psi ]]></fr:tex>. To see this, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_{i}\}]]></fr:tex> be a basis of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M/N]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi (\psi (e_{i}))=e_{i}]]></fr:tex> for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>(2) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T=\psi (M / N)]]></fr:tex> is such a complement. We just need to check <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[T\cap  N=\emptyset ]]></fr:tex>, which is an exercise.</fr:p><html:span
